:"1432","1344":"1344","1365":"1365","1453":"1453","1386":"1386","1328":"1328","Defford, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Defford, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom","Defford, Worcestershire, England":"Defford, Worcestershire, England","Hampshire, England":"Hampshire, England","Badby, Northamptonshire, England":"Badby, Northamptonshire, England"},"nl":{"1326–1432":"1326–1432","1344–1362":"1344–1362","1362–1435":"1362–1435","1290–1386":"1290–1386","1305–1386":"1305–1386","AFT 1386":"na 1386","1362":"1362","1382":"1382","1290":"1290","Abt 1362":"circa 1362","1305":"1305","1326":"1326","1337":"1337","1435":"1435","1432":"1432","1344":"1344","1365":"1365","1453":"1453","1386":"1386","1328":"1328","Defford, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Defford, Worcestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Defford, Worcestershire, England":"Defford, Worcestershire, England","Hampshire, England":"Hampshire, England","Badby, Northamptonshire, England":"Badby, Northamptonshire, England"},"en":{"1326–1432":"1326–1432","1344–1362":"1344–1362","1362–1435":"1362–1435","1290–1386":"1290–1386","1305–1386":"1305–1386","AFT 1386":"after 1386","1362":"1362","1382":"1382","1290":"1290","Abt 1362":"about 1362","1305":"1305","1326":"1326","1337":"1337","1435":"1435","1432":"1432","1344":"1344","1365":"1365","1453":"1453","1386":"1386","1328":"1328","Defford, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Defford, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom","Defford, Worcestershire, England":"Defford, Worcestershire, England","Hampshire, England":"Hampshire, England","Badby, Northamptonshire, England":"Badby, Northamptonshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Spencer","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): occupational name for someone who dispensed provisions or money, from Middle English <i>spenser(e)</i>, <i>spencer(e)</i> ‘household steward, butler, almoner’ (Anglo-Norman French <i>espenser</i>, Old French <i>despensier</i>). Compare   Spence   and   Spender  . There is some dispute about the origins of the Spencer family, whose most famous member in recent times was the late Princess of Wales, born Lady Diana Spencer (1961–97). Some sources say that they are descended from William the Conqueror's steward, Robert Despencer. What is clear is that by the 15th century they had become prosperous from sheep farming in Northamptonshire. Robert Spencer (died 1627) was said to be the wealthiest man in England. Their titles have included Earls of Sunderland and Earls Spencer; and through the female line the 5th Earl of Sunderland also became Duke of Marlborough in 1733. This connection was the result of the marriage, in 1700, of the 3rd Duke of Sunderland to the daughter of John Churchill, 1st Duke of Marlborough. The youngest son of this union, John Spencer (1708–46), was the father of the 1st Earl Spencer (1734–83)."],"variants":[{"name":"Spence","meanings":["English and Scottish: nickname for a servant employed in the pantry of a great house or monastery, from Middle English <i>spense</i>, <i>spence</i> ‘pantry, larder, storeroom’ (Old French <i>despense</i>, from a Late Latin derivative of <i>dispendere</i>, past participle <i>dispensus</i> ‘to weigh out or dispense’). Compare   Spencer  ."]},{"name":"Spenser","meanings":["English: variant of   Spencer  ."]},{"name":"Spender","meanings":["English:","occupational name or status name from Middle English <i>spender(e)</i>, <i>spendour</i> ‘steward, treasurer’, a shortened form of Middle English, Old French <i>despendour</i>, denoting someone who managed money or supplies. Compare   Spencer  .","alternatively, perhaps a nickname from Middle English <i>spender(e)</i>, <i>spendour</i> ‘spender (of money), spendthrift’."]}]},{"name":"Nicholas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the post-classical Greek personal name <i>Nikolaos</i>, derived from <i>nikē</i> ‘victory’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’. The spelling with <i>-ch-</i> first occurred as early as the 12th century, and became firmly established at the time of the Reformation, although  <b>Nicolas</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Nickolas","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: variant spelling of   Nicholas  , influenced by the short form   Nick ."]},{"name":"Nicolas","meanings":["From Late Greek.  See  <b>Nicholas</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705192,"age":2,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":11,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":56,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Nicholas De Spencer was born in 1326, in Defford, Worcestershire, England, his father, Lord John De Spencer, was 37 and his mother, Lady Alice Elizabeth Deverell, was 21. He married Joan Pollard in 1365, in Hampshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1432, in his hometown, at the age of 106."},"et":{"1326–1432":"1326–1432","1344–1362":"1344–1362","1362–1435":"1362–1435","1290–1386":"1290–1386","1305–1386":"1305–1386","AFT 1386":"pärast 1386","1362":"1362","1382":"1382","1290":"1290","Abt 1362":"umbes 1362","1305":"1305","1326":"1326","1337":"1337","1435":"1435","1432":"1432","1344":"1344","1365":"1365","1453":"1453","1386":"1386","1328":"1328","Defford, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Defford, Worcestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Defford, Worcestershire, England":"Defford, Worcestershire, England","Hampshire, England":"Hampshire, England","Badby, Northamptonshire, England":"Badby, Northamptonshire, England"},"fi":{"1326–1432":"1326–1432","1344–1362":"1344–1362","1362–1435":"1362–1435","1290–1386":"1290–1386","1305–1386":"1305–1386","AFT 1386":"1386 jälkeen","1362":"1362","1382":"1382","1290":"1290","Abt 1362":"noin 1362","1305":"1305","13